<br />
ah ok thanks, i was not familiar with the jargon <img src="images/smilies/smile.gif" border="0" alt="" title="Smilie" class="inlineimg" /><br />
<br />
yes i definatly see your point, as for the targeting ring, would it work like you mouse over your ability and it shows the radious with some visual graphic?<br />
<br />
Like we we target a mob and mouse over fire ball, it would show the aoe's radious around the foe? That would be handy.<br />
<br />
<br />
<br />
I would say that it is a rather segnificant difference if it is an aura rather than a ranged aoe buff centered on the defensive target:<br />
<br />
Eq2 for example, it really sucks to use the druid's AOE blocking ability: It only works on the group we are in, has a 3 meter radius, and has no visual marking about it's radius, AND if an ally moves into its effect range after triggered, it wont apply to them. And it makes the druid unable to cast.<br />
<br />
Its the prime example of how not to do anything related to aoe prevention <img src="images/smilies/smile.gif" border="0" alt="" title="Smilie" class="inlineimg" /><br />
<br />
The biggest issue is the not applying when people get in range. Not only to people have to be practically humping the druid in a large cluster, it has to be right as i cast it, when means the entirety of the fight you have like 23 people clustered in a 3m radius just so they dont accedentally miss it lol... so epic!<br />
<br />
<br />
<br />
I wouldnt think that it would take too many Zots to apply the aura mechanic to the sanctuary spells though, since all the mechanics are already in place.<br />
<br />
Both bard songs and DC and Pally Auras all pulse effects from a given point of orgin (the player), and we have the ability to maintain effects on players (see disciple's bonds), so combining both mechanics should produce the desired result.<br />
<br />
The ability to maintain a graphic on an ally should be highly trivial; this is a basic requirement for any spell with a visual (aka, if you move while showing a buff or heal's graphic, it moves with you, in some cases leaving a cloud trail)<br />
<br />
<br />
So, the sorcerer would &quot;maintain&quot; an effect on their defensive target, that give them the &quot;aura&quot; buff which has the actual sanctuary effect that pulses constantly on any ally in the area. The graphic would be played at the defensive targets location, and would basically remain centered on the player, regardless of movement.<br />
<br />
Same concept as those little &quot;marks&quot; we can place on allies as a group/raid leader, they stay centered on the target regardless of movement.<br />
<br />
<br />
Its all about combining what we have into a workable form.<br />
<br />
If the coders can examine how current abilities function, shouldnt they be able to whip up my example in under and hour?
                  
