				&nbsp;<br />
				<div>   </div>
			</div>				
	
	
	
	</td>
	
	<td class="alt1" id="td_post_1238013">
	
		
		<!-- message -->
		<div id="post_message_1238013">
                  
                  <div style="margin:20px; margin-top:5px; ">
	<div class="smallfont" style="margin-bottom:2px">Quote:</div>
	<table cellpadding="6" cellspacing="0" border="0" width="100%">
	<tr>
		<td class="alt2" style="border:1px inset">
			
				<div>Originally Posted by <strong>Drkpl2</strong></div>
				<div style="font-style:italic">Well, to make it all more difficult, I would have to agree with Emi on the fact that if a &quot;Shield&quot; is implimented it will come at the cost of DPS.  Just being in procimity of a Sorc, does not mean that anyone should have &quot;Shielding&quot; form incoming spells.<br />
A Sorc should still have to put forth effort to &quot;Shield&quot; the ones near them from incoming spells, and that is going to come at the cost that they most stop their DPS to accomidate those that need protection.  At least not automaticly.  Make it a proc chance, yeah then I would agree, because that leaves that the Sorc must do something to make the &quot;Shielding&quot; happen.  Or are we speaking of leaving it a spell that the Sorc still must cast, then I would agree.  But if we are talking about a aura or dance or song, then no.  I would rather see us focus on the DPS side of things.</div>
			
		</td>
	</tr>
	</table>
</div>
<br />
An instant cast with a 2 second cool down really wont mean squat in terms of lowering dps, especially if you consider the shear about of dps allowed when the raid doesnt have to take those 8 seconds or so to joust in an our to avoid near certain death, not to mention lag making some people get caught by the aoe potientially.<br />
<br />
<br />
<br />
Also think about this:<br />
<br />
We already cannot go &quot;all out&quot; on a raid and expect to live.<br />
<br />
The majoity of the raid fights i have played in several games are NOT about who can get the highest dps, its about who can maintain the highest dps with out dieing or being a detrement to the raid.<br />
<br />
<br />
That is why i absolutely loved my conjuror in eq2 raiding.<br />
<br />
I would usually not match a sorcerer's dps, but i could get close, and would be much less likely to steal hate because:<br />
<br />
IF a sorcerer is doing 2400 dps, its all going to him. If im doing 2200 dps, 1500 or so might be mine, but 700 is likely from my pet. As we dont share hate pools unless my pet dies (in which then it is transfered to me), i can reach much higher and consitant dps early on in a fight with little to no worries about stealing hate.<br />
<br />
So, at some point, they IS such a thing as &quot;too much damage&quot; at the wrong time.<br />
<br />
<br />
So, really you should almost at some point ask yourself &quot;in times where i cant go all out due to hate restrictions in a non-burn part of the fight, how else can i also contribute a really helpful effect to the raid beyond leet dps?&quot;<br />
<br />
For us, i think spell defense, if they can ever find a good mechanic for it, will be our idea secondary asset.<br />
<br />
<br />
Each caster can offer other things besides dps:<br />
<br />
<br />
A druid while all their dots are on the mob and are in their &quot;paced&quot; dps mode usually has time to spot heal and toss up an emergency 2 hit absorb rune or toss out some vital calamities/wonders.<br />
<br />
A necro (hopefully eventually) might get some minions that could be particularly helpful for debilitating a foe or something such, or animate a reciently killed add for some good extra damage, or debuff the foe.<br />
<br />
A psionicist probably has the most things to offer when not in &quot;full damage&quot; mode: Hate reduction (which needs some SERIOUS increasing imo, never got its 100% boost), Energy refilling, dropping a minor shield to hopefully help someone live, and CC when appropriate.<br />
<br />
<br />
<br />
Is every encounter going to need CC? Or &quot;extra&quot; healing / emegency spells? Or special minions or something necro-related?<br />
<br />
Not likely.<br />
<br />
Just as not every encounter will need our spell defense.<br />
<br />
But, there will be times and places (likely frequently) where all 4 of our sub roles will see some definate use, just none will be exclusively &quot;required&quot; for all contient. Hopefully anyway if it is balanced correctly!
                  
		</div>
		<!-- / message -->
	
		
		
		
		
		
	
	</td>
</tr>
